The Scorched Wastes -- Rakuen Perspective

Ember Wardens send a delegation east every third year to witness the Wastes firsthand. Not for trade or negotiation.

Formerly the Meridian Intake March: functional institutions, living clerks, codified law. Worked like Midgaard works -- through process, ledger, and stamped seal. The Ninth Meridian Rite failed when it tried to fuse solar measurement with underworld descent authority. Heat surged through dry water channels. Governance burned.

Garden Ledger Clerks keep a charred charter fragment from the Wastes beside Rakuen's own Southward Compact. It still bears a toll stamp, witness seal, and half a ration schedule. The system was functioning perfectly when it destroyed everything it protected.

Charter Remnants are clerks who outlived their civilization but not their procedures. They stamp, seal, and file in a kingdom of glass and cinder, killing for missing paperwork. Bloom Pavilion philosopher Ivren Tal called them "the honest mirror of the Midgaard clerk" -- both serve process rather than people.

Dune Host Reavers hoard water containers and legal tablets equally; both are currency in the Wastes. Synod Eclipse Cells stage mock tribunals and witness-burning rites, insisting the failed synthesis can be corrected.

Rooms show former purpose and post-catastrophe reuse: verdict halls held by revenants, toll stones recut as curses, ration seals worn by raiders.

Ember Wardens carve "law persists after legitimacy dies" into every Cracked Promise Stone. Rakuen was called a failed paradise. The Wastes are a successful bureaucracy. Rakuen knows which failure it prefers.

